properties.description:
The Golden Fish

The Golden Fish is a fish and chip shop on Becontree Avenue in Dagenham that has been in business for about 50 years. ⁣ ⁣ It has the perfect sign: 13 thick, obvious letters sit above two uncomplicated fish who face each other like lifelong friends or enemies, reflecting back the same fins, tails and barely perceptible mouths.⁣ ⁣ This drama takes place in a loud shade of yellow-orange, set against a backdrop of deep blue, a striking colour combination also used in the IKEA logo. ⁣ ⁣ So the sign’s colour scheme is a big part of its magic, but it stands out mainly because it belongs to another time.⁣ ⁣ It isn’t a single, readymade thing that someone stuck up in one go: its background is formed of two panels, which the lettering and illustrations are affixed on top of, so they don’t just look like they’re jumping out from the surface, they actually are.⁣ ⁣ It’s the kind of sign that could lose a component to a strong enough wind, that shows the hand of the person who designed and installed it.⁣ ⁣ Inside, the place expresses itself in a different way: all bouncy red booths and stained glass windows, along with these peach and marble effect wall panels that literally suck you into the dining room.⁣ ⁣ I’ve sat in this room a couple of times now and it’s clearly well-used by local people, like a distilled version of the vibe at Something Fishy in Lewisham, a much larger sit-down chip shop.⁣ ⁣ When I went a couple of Saturdays ago at 4.30pm, as it was getting dark outside, The Golden Fish was only beginning to fill up. ⁣ ⁣ It was just me and a couple in there, before this jovial guy burst through the door, greeted the staff behind the counter by saying “good evening ladies and gentlemen”, and then asked them for a large rock.⁣ ⁣ After that he sat down and the waitress checked if he was having his usual order, which also included bread and a cup of tea.⁣ ⁣ When I came back last Friday at lunchtime, the place was already full, and many of its customers had grey hair.⁣ ⁣ Most people were quietly working through their meals, but two guys on separate tables were chatting, one of them telling the other that he used to come here with his dad when he was a kid.

properties.description:
Dumplings Legend

You’ve probably been to Dumplings' Legend enough times to know how arriving there works: you walk up a couple of steps and open the glass doors, at which point someone immediately greets you, confirms your party size and passes you to another member of staff who takes you to your table. ⁣ ⁣ If you happen to have a dripping umbrella in your hand, they’ll kindly pop it into a plastic bag for you, often so swiftly you barely even realise it’s happening.⁣ ⁣ If you’re eating alone, there’s a high chance you’ll end up in the part of the dining room by the big window that looks out onto Gerrard Street, made up mostly of closely configured two-seater tables.⁣ ⁣ On a good day, you’ll get one right by this window, where squeezing into your seat is slightly less trouble, since you aren’t sandwiched between two sets of people.⁣ ⁣ These roomier spots are also an excellent place to watch Chinatown go by, as well as the section of the restaurant with the most natural light.⁣ ⁣ Here, as with everywhere else in this colossal eating place, you may notice how each chair has these distinctive black and white seat covers, stretched taut enough to skew their chequerboard pattern and create a mildly hypnotic optical illusion.⁣ ⁣ Many different people occupy these chairs and this part of the room, but at lunchtime on a weekday it does tend to attract a few classic types. ⁣ ⁣ These include pairs of old friends gossiping over tea and turnip cakes, along with small family units of domestic and international tourists, visibly relieved to have escaped the frantic streets outside.⁣ ⁣ Almost always there is at least one parent with a child: a mum eating cheung fun while her kid plays on an iPad, for example, or a dad eating xiaolongbao as passing staff stop to stroke his baby’s plump cheeks.⁣ ⁣ Outside of peak times, you might spot these same friendly staff members periodically looking out of the big window in a peaceful way, like you might do with a painting in a gallery.⁣ ⁣ That’s because Dumplings’ Legend isn’t just a perpetually busy multifloor restaurant, it’s also a well-ordered one, which copes well with the hundreds of people that must pass through its doors each day.

properties.description:
Beyti, Green Lanes

I find Beyti in Stoke Newington interesting because it contains fragments of a not-too-distant past, the most compelling of which is a boxing glove signed by former world heavyweight champion Lennox Lewis.⁣ ⁣ I haven’t yet asked the restaurant’s owners how long their walls have been collecting things like this, but I reckon their business has been around for more than two decades. ⁣ ⁣ My basis for this is the landline number on the sign outside that starts with 0171, a dialling code that was taken out of service 24 years ago; inside, there’s also several framed copies of a review from the second edition of Time Out’s Cheap Eats in London, a book published in 2004.⁣ ⁣ There’s lots of other distinctive items on the wall here too, which have only recently started to look like they belong to a different time.⁣ ⁣ Take the painting of a rural scene, with a cottage by a stream and some coniferous trees and a misty mountain range in the distance, patinated by years of grill smoke. ⁣ ⁣ Then there’s the poster on the other side of the room, which shows a dramatic valley and a body of water that ends with a mosque, its blues and greens vivid in a way that reminds me of the pages of an old magazine. ⁣ ⁣ I learned from the caption of this image that it depicts a lake called Uzungöl in Turkey’s Trabzon Province, while the picture next to it shows Pamukkale, a series of terraced hot springs.⁣ ⁣ The Pamukkale poster also has two smaller, dog-eared photos tucked into its frame’s corners, something that encapsulates precisely what I love about old places: their layers of history show wear and evidence of use and they relate to real people. ⁣ ⁣ Here those people appear to be a group of customers enjoying a meal and a guy behind the grill, two things that still happen at Beyti today.⁣ ⁣ On my first visit here, the person behind the grill these days cooked me a coarse, fat-laden Adana kebab.⁣ ⁣ When I came back for the lamb beyti, it made me think just how much dishes of minced grilled lamb like this are so uncomplicatedly about eating for pleasure.⁣ ⁣ I felt that once more when I went for the akçaabat köfte, which tasted to me like a heap of small, excellent burgers.

properties.description:
Rheidol Terrace

Nowhere catches the sunlight quite like @rheidol_rooms in Islington, a place I’ve recently learned must be among London’s most historical caffs. ⁣ ⁣ While the dining room has a few newer furnishings too, its key features hint at serious oldness, from the lemon chiffon Formica to the intriguing cutlery station by the counter, which has the wear and darkening of decades of use.⁣ ⁣ The floor tiles also have these lovely intricate circular designs, just like the ones at Scotti’s Snack Bar in Clerkenwell.⁣ ⁣ But it’s the place’s worn, slender chairs that struck me most on my first visit, mainly because they made me think of the truly museum-worthy ones at @theelectriccafe in West Norwood.⁣ ⁣ When I asked the friendly lady who runs Rheidol Rooms how old her business was, she wasn't able to give me an exact date, though she did say that her grandmother used to work here and that she thinks the place could be a century old.⁣ ⁣ She then pointed me towards a black and white photo on the wall, which I can see was taken just up the road on St Peter’s Street and shows Rheidol Rooms in the background, noticeable by its curved exterior. ⁣ ⁣ You can just about make out that it used to have a different sign; if you walk up to where the picture was taken, there’s still a postbox in the same spot. ⁣ ⁣ I still find it remarkable that London has ordinary restaurants this old, that operate without fanfare and just do the same stuff they’ve always done, like cooking simple meals, making customers feel welcome and giving people somewhere to sit down for a while.⁣ ⁣ When I’ve sat down here and eaten something myself, I’ve particularly enjoyed the club sandwich, something I always try to get if I see it on a menu. ⁣ ⁣ You’ll hear the cook bash down a chicken breast before throwing it on the grill, as he proceeds to make the other components of what I now realise could also be described as a chicken BLT. ⁣ ⁣ I love their smaller fry-up option too, which has got to be up there with my favourites in the city. ⁣ ⁣ It reminded me of a pivotal breakfast experience I had at @marioscaff in Kentish Town, which made me understand that all you really need is egg, bacon, sausage and tomato.

properties.description:
Lanzhou Noodle Bar

I usually find myself walking to Lanzhou Lamian from Piccadilly, past the Eros statue, along Coventry Street and through the busiest bit of Leicester Square, a journey I wouldn’t wish on anyone.⁣ ⁣ Along with all the slow walkers and immovable crowds, there’s loads of other things that bring out a misanthropy in me I didn’t know I had, from the floating bronze of Harry Potter to that giant, overcomplicated, entirely nonsensical Swiss clock.⁣ ⁣ Yet Lanzhou Lamian is hardly any less hectic than its surroundings; it just isn’t fake or tacky or grossly overpriced. ⁣ ⁣ Even when it's overflowing with people, the restaurant’s attentive staff swiftly marshall you inside, and if you’re eating in, tell you precisely which part of which communal table to sit at. ⁣ ⁣ After a visit or two, I stopped worrying about getting in people’s way or the complexities of squeezing into my seat, not long before I realised I actually felt quite comfortable here. ⁣ ⁣ It’s a simple dining room, adorned with little other than red, green, yellow and orange paint.⁣ ⁣ What makes it interesting is its open kitchen, which is occupied by at least four people at any one time, who prepare and cook food beneath clouds of steam and an extraction fan the size of a projector screen. ⁣ ⁣ So there’s lots of whirring and whooshing and the scrape of metal on metal, along with the occasional crackle of something being plunged into hot oil. ⁣ ⁣ But the coolest thing is obviously the sculptor you pass as you arrive and pay, who spends all day turning sausagey lumps of dough into elegant noodles, rolling, stretching and twisting each strand until they literally become as thin as angel hair.⁣ ⁣ I imagine you can’t go too far wrong with any menu item here that features his work, and I’ve enjoyed working my way through a few of them lately. ⁣ ⁣ But I’m always drawn back to the stewed beef in soup form, which is probably the place’s most popular dish.⁣ ⁣ The brisket is almost sweet; the broth blinking with a thousand eyes of fat, rich enough to coat your lips with each sip.⁣ ⁣ I like to eat it in two stages: first, without any chilli oil and then near the end, I turn the whole thing into a glowing red mass.

Even when it's overflowing with people, the restaurant’s attentive staff swiftly marshall you inside, and if you’re eating in, tell you precisely which part of which communal table to sit at. ⁣
⁣
After a visit or two, I stopped worrying about getting in people’s way or the complexities of squeezing into my seat, not long before I realised I actually felt quite comfortable here. ⁣
⁣
It’s a simple dining room, adorned with little other than red, green, yellow and orange paint.⁣
⁣
What makes it interesting is its open kitchen, which is occupied by at least four people at any one time, who prepare and cook food beneath clouds of steam and an extraction fan the size of a projector screen. ⁣
⁣
So there’s lots of whirring and whooshing and the scrape of metal on metal, along with the occasional crackle of something being plunged into hot oil. ⁣
⁣
But the coolest thing is obviously the sculptor you pass as you arrive and pay, who spends all day turning sausagey lumps of dough into elegant noodles, rolling, stretching and twisting each strand until they literally become as thin as angel hair.⁣
⁣
I imagine you can’t go too far wrong with any menu item here that features his work, and I’ve enjoyed working my way through a few of them lately. ⁣
⁣
But I’m always drawn back to the stewed beef in soup form, which is probably the place’s most popular dish.⁣
⁣
The brisket is almost sweet; the broth blinking with a thousand eyes of fat, rich enough to coat your lips with each sip.⁣
⁣
I like to eat it in two stages: first, without any chilli oil and then near the end, I turn the whole thing into a glowing red mass.

properties.description:
Ivy's

I’ve been running this page for over four years now, and while I like to write about other restaurants on here too, I’m still fascinated by caffs. ⁣ ⁣ I think the main reason I’ve stayed interested in caffs all these years is that each place has its own little quirks and idiosyncrasies, particularly the really old ones.⁣ ⁣ Such as Ivy’s, which has operated out of Poplar’s Chrisp Street Market since 1951, and differs from other historical spots by having its seating area entirely outside. ⁣ ⁣ Since they spend their time outdoors, it makes sense that the chairs and tables are made of plastic and stainless steel.⁣ ⁣ The kitchen and counter area are the place’s only truly permanent fixtures, around which these weatherproof furnishings disappear and reappear each working day. ⁣ ⁣ Yet this seating area is as atmospheric as London’s oldest, wood-panelled spots.⁣ ⁣ That’s because Ivy’s is so well-used, catering to people who live locally and regularly pass through the 72 year-old shopping area that surrounds it, in much the same way as Randolfi’s in Bow and Something Fishy in Lewisham, two other marketplace caffs.⁣ ⁣ In the morning I’ve seen customers in woolly hats congregating beneath the place’s awning, patiently waiting for Ivy’s to open up.⁣ ⁣ At lunchtime I’ve seen groups laughing over board games, and a kid sent down to collect a sandwich order for his family.⁣ ⁣ Up until recently, you could get things like pease pudding and faggots at Ivy’s, but they stopped serving them earlier this year after demand slowly reduced. ⁣ ⁣ They still do saveloys though, another dish which has been eaten in this part of London for ages, which here are firmer and more conventionally sausage-like than any saveloy I’ve ever had. ⁣ ⁣ Their crusty rolls are similarly dignified, so much so that they sometimes literally stand upright, especially with a burger inside them, that melds nicely with the cheese and onions you may opt to have it with.⁣ ⁣ I’ve been particularly struck by the uniqueness of their fry-up; it comes with these distinctive little sausages and the bacon still sizzling. ⁣ ⁣ Since you can also get all of its components in a roll, they call it “a breakfast on a plate”.

properties.description:
Castle's Traditional Pie & Mash

Step inside Castle’s Pie & Mash and you may notice a bit of warmth and water vapour in the air.⁣ ⁣ It’s a light, pleasant type of humidity unique to pie and mash shops, which must be down to the gigantic pots of potatoes and parsley sauce that bubble away in the back. ⁣ ⁣ Then there’s the sheer number of pies these places bake, a process you can observe more easily at Castle’s, since the wood-panelled oven that cooks them is in the dining room, blending in nicely with the place’s walls.⁣ ⁣ I don’t know how old that panelling is, but the business has existed for almost nine decades; my guess is its fixed plastic seating was fitted more recently though. ⁣ ⁣ I like how those smooth chairs are the same burnt umber colour as the sign outside, which is also unusual because the words “traditional pie & mash” are in all caps rather than the name of the family who founded the place.⁣ ⁣ Along with the swirly lettering of “Castle’s”, I’m fascinated by the shortness of the phone number, which I learned features a remnant of the old local telephone exchange code for Kentish Town. ⁣ ⁣ Lots of regular customers still pass underneath that sign each week, including families, groups of friends and older patrons who are greeted by name.⁣ ⁣ When I’ve eaten here, I've always been served by the same untiring guy, who concentrates on assembling the plate of the customer in front of him before looking up and taking the order of the next person in line. ⁣ ⁣ The pies, mash and liquor are behind the counter, so he looks after those, but he shouts tea, dessert and hot eels orders into the back.⁣ ⁣ Every now and then someone leaves the kitchen to carry something through or open the oven and spin the pans around, like you might do with a frozen pizza at home. ⁣ ⁣ The operation works well and has clearly been in place for a long time, so the queue moves at a steady rate and you feel relaxed being a part of it. ⁣ ⁣ While you’re waiting, you may also notice a window-like hole built in the counter, where you can see the cash register; I’m not sure if that means the fittings here were custom-made, but I like to think they were.

properties.description:
Yipin China

Restaurants are public rooms with chairs and scuffed floorboards and pictures on the walls, where you can pay to sit down for a while as people cook food and bring it over to you. ⁣ ⁣ I’ve recently become interested in one such room on a residential street in Islington, called Yipin China, where the afternoon light streams in through the windows beautifully even if it’s drizzly and overcast outside. ⁣ ⁣ If you arrive early enough, you can get the whole place to yourself, which is precisely what happened when I came here for the first time, alone on a bank holiday Sunday in May, before meeting some friends somewhere else. ⁣ ⁣ On that visit I ordered the hot dry noodles, a deeply savoury bowl of food with things like chilli oil and sesame paste in it.⁣ ⁣ I chose that dish because it seemed similar to one I like at Dr Noodle in New Cross and I ate it between sips of pale Chinese lager, with the kind of happy satisfaction you get when you know you have the day off tomorrow as well, as my phone charged at the empty table next to me.⁣ ⁣ This quiet eating experience stayed with me all summer, like the vague memory of a good dream.⁣ ⁣ When my impressions of that meal began to fade, I decided it was time to go back again and try some stuff from the Hunan and Sichuan sections of the place’s menu. ⁣ ⁣ On Thursday last week, my impulse was to order the red braised pork belly, a dish that reminds me of the strata of sedimentary rock: you get the layers of pure fat, which vanish in your mouth like hot jelly, alongside those leaner bits of meat which hold more of the clove-like flavour of star anise. ⁣ ⁣ Rather than being too samey, each cuboid of pork feels different and kind of alive; I love how you can slice between their alternating layers with a chopstick, if they haven’t already come apart by themselves.⁣ ⁣ My experiences with the mapo tofu and the herbal chicken soup have been similarly compelling, particularly the soup.⁣ ⁣ The broth was milky and medicinal in a way I don't think I’ve encountered before, yet it tasted incredibly familiar. ⁣ ⁣ It made me feel hungrier as I ate it and must be the most nourishing thing I’ve eaten in a long time.

properties.description:
Bar Bruno

I wasted a lot of time not going to Bar Bruno over the years, mainly because I thought its revamped signage meant its interior had been entirely refurbished too. ⁣ ⁣ But I was wrong: they still have this great, time-honoured Coke lampshade by the counter, along with those wonderfully dimpled booths and banquettes, which are the same myrtle green as the ones at Beppe’s in Smithfield. ⁣ ⁣ It’s true that some of the panelling has been obscured by the newer digital collage on the walls, but the wood you can see wears its age well.⁣ ⁣ It remains a dignified room, which is sympathetic to the people who enter it, especially if you get there outside of the lunch rush, when it’s easier to get a seat.⁣ ⁣ Of course, that fellow feeling is expressed more clearly by the industrious staff who make the place what it is, like the waitress who calls everyone “baby” and the waiter who pretends to be cynical and world-weary but is really just as caring, who I saw address a customer wearing all navy as “Mr Blue”.⁣ ⁣ It was that breakfast and some other recent visits that made me think Bar Bruno must be one of the few places around here that actually has regulars.⁣ ⁣ It’s a busy spot, that also welcomes a lot of passing trade, but the crowd is still nicely mixed: there are as many lanyards and thick-rimmed glasses as there are fleeces, high-vis and heavy boots.⁣ ⁣ If you do happen to be a returning customer, the staff are likely to recall your previous order, like the man I saw confirm he wanted the same fry-up variant again, with “everything well done”; when his food arrived, it featured a neatly butterflied sausage with a grill-marked interior.⁣ ⁣ I’m more into the lunch and evening menu items myself, such as the liver, which I tried for the first time when I came here with my dad and I found needed some HP mixed into the gravy, to offset the mellow sameyness.⁣ ⁣ I really like the BLT too, which is among the cheaper options here. ⁣ ⁣ If you do get one, you’ll be asked two questions: if you want mayo and if you want your bread toasted. ⁣ ⁣ After giving it some careful thought, and sampling both options, I find that the soft, doorstep slices here are best enjoyed as they are.

properties.description:
Billingsgate Fish Market

I got up relatively early and went to Billingsgate fish market last week, around that time when the tube has a quieter, more focused crowd of commuting workers and it’s a lot easier to get a seat.⁣ ⁣ After racing through one of Canary Wharf’s airport-like shopping centres, then over a bridge across the dark water, I achieved my goal of getting to the market before 6.30am. ⁣ ⁣ Even then I could see it was beginning to wind down, but there were still lots of people.⁣ ⁣ The stalls were still very much in operation, which is more than I can say for the other time I’d been, when I arrived just before 8am and the only traders left were packing up. ⁣ ⁣ What I noticed on this visit was all the movement: it really is a gigantic, slippery warehouse full of squeaking wellies; there’s loads of polystyrene boxes and wooden pallets being dragged around and the endless shovelling of ice, as people buy and sell fish under the bright unnatural light. ⁣ ⁣ I bought something myself, but I was mainly there to get a sense of the place and check out one specific stall for a longer piece of writing I'm working on. ⁣ ⁣ I thought I might stick out as someone primarily interested in looking around, but it’s a public marketplace so obviously no one cares.⁣ ⁣ I found the sheer volume of everything really compelling, from the height of the ceiling to the boxes of russet brown crabs, maybe because they seem so prehistoric to me and I’m not used to seeing so many of them together.⁣ ⁣ Then there’s the whole eels, and the stuff from further afield, like doctor fish and black pomfret, sometimes with a single fish on display, as if it’s an elected representative for its entire species. ⁣ ⁣ When I’d got my fill of looking at fish I went to the Billingsgate Cafe, a fascinating place and the reason I came to the market last time.⁣ ⁣ They do a scallop bacon roll, so I got that again, more because the dish exists than anything else. ⁣ ⁣ I saw some market traders eating cheeseburgers, so maybe that’s actually the better thing to get here.⁣ ⁣ You see them strolling in and greeting the staff like old friends, some of them bypassing the middleman at the counter to shout their orders directly to the chef.

⁣

properties.description:
Wamimichi Noodle Bar 和味道港式茶餐廳

One of the restaurants that’s stayed with me the most this year is Wamimichi Noodle Bar in Hendon, for a few reasons.⁣ ⁣ I originally became interested in the place because of its connection with the recent wave of migration of people from Hong Kong to the UK, which I touched on when I wrote about it for @vittlesmagazine back in June. ⁣ ⁣ I was struck by the character of the place, which seemed to me like a blend of there and here. ⁣ ⁣ Along with all the Hong Kong-related things everywhere, like the Chinese ham flavoured chicken stock cubes by the counter, there was lots of Union Jack bunting left over from the coronation.⁣ ⁣ I don’t live nearby and I’ve been back to the area a few times lately, to visit Wamimichi again and check out another place over the road.⁣ ⁣ These recent trips have made me think about my experiences travelling to Hendon, which I associate with sitting on the Northern Line for a while; on the Edgware branch, I’m still surprised when you pop out into the light at Golders Green and suddenly get 4G again. ⁣ ⁣ I also find it interesting how Brent Cross and Hendon Central stations are so similar, with all their oldness and chequerboard floors.⁣ ⁣ I like all the overpasses and underpasses around here too, which remind me of bits of Chiswick and Neasden.⁣ ⁣ Wamimichi offers an escape from all that main roadness, even though a few large panes of glass are all that separate you from the whooshing of Hendon Way outside.⁣ ⁣ Inside, I’ve noticed the bunting has since been exchanged for birthday decorations, but the place still has that distinctive feeling of somewhere that’s been recently refurbished, as if it’s both old and new at the same time.⁣ ⁣ The dining room has a lot going on, which is what makes it so compelling, like the laksa I tried last week.⁣ ⁣ I’ve only had one of these before, at Cafe TPT in Chinatown, which I loved and struggled to finish.⁣ ⁣ There’s several laksas on the menu here, but I went for the “house” one, which features pork, prawn, chicken, tofu, half a boiled egg and a thousand other ingredients. ⁣ ⁣ I was working through it for ages before it occurred to me there’d be a delicious clump of noodles at the bottom too.

properties.description:
The River Cafe

I’ve written about the River Cafe’s beautiful sign, chairs, tables, mirrors, ceiling, tilework, wall art, columns, coat hooks, light fixtures and Juventus memorabilia loads of times before, so I won’t go into them again here.⁣ ⁣ What’s more important anyway is how all of these features contribute to the dining room’s overall humanity, which is also shaped by its size and layout. ⁣ ⁣ Just as E Pellicci's unique atmosphere is connected to its compactness, I think the River Cafe is all about space.⁣ ⁣ I love both vibes and I think they achieve something similar: rooms you feel comfortable spending time in, whether you’re alone, with a companion or hanging out in a larger group.⁣ ⁣ You’re less likely to have to squeeze past another customer at the River Cafe, but the place is still full of life and movement and clatter and conversation; it’s just that it’s all dispersed across a wider area. ⁣ ⁣ The restaurant also has a quietly high ceiling, something I’ve noticed tends to make a room seem bigger than it really is. ⁣ ⁣ This airiness makes you feel pleasantly small, more proof that even large spaces can be cosy.⁣ ⁣ A lot of my favourite spots have this canteen or dining hall-like spirit, which you feel especially strongly at places where you order at the counter, and table service is largely restricted to the collecting and bringing out of plates.⁣ ⁣ In this context tables become more about eating and sitting than anything else, especially if they’re communal, as they are at the River Cafe.⁣ ⁣ My favourite place to sit here is the set of tables at the back, below the clock and the room’s most striking coastal scene.⁣ ⁣ I’ve eaten various dishes sat there, such as a dignified, beanless fry-up and an apple crumble with custard.⁣ ⁣ I only recently realised they have a chicken escalope on the menu here too, which I really like, along with the tender heap of spaghetti it comes with. ⁣ ⁣ When I had that dish for the first time, the place’s staff were bringing out plates for a group of a dozen or so tanned Italian tourists, who spilled over several conjoined tables and all looked quite pleased with their roast dinners, jacket potatoes and omelettes with chips.

properties.description:
Chini Chor

As with sit-down chippies, I’m particularly drawn to mithai shops where you can eat in, because they allow you to get a better sense of the place’s personality.⁣ ⁣ Chini Chor’s personality, like many other places that sell South Asian sweets and savoury snacks, is defined by its glass display cabinets, which are lined with vivid confectionery and buried under loads of fried and dried things. ⁣ ⁣ People pop in for stuff to take away, but it’s very much a functioning restaurant too, even though it only has several tables.⁣ ⁣ The food comes out quickly and doesn’t cost much; if you wanted to, you could eat a couple of things and be in and out within ten minutes. ⁣ ⁣ I’ve done just that a few times, once after a seamless 24 minute journey from Soho to Southall. ⁣ ⁣ Every time I’ve been I’ve noticed other diners also enjoying Chini Chor's various chaats, which push the limit of what a snack can be.⁣ ⁣ I find that the aloo tikki chaat, with its quietly extensive list of soft, sour, sweet, spicy, smoky and crunchy components, makes for a great light lunch.⁣ ⁣ The same goes for the Punjabi samosa chaat, which is piled high and almost spilling over. ⁣ ⁣ I love samosas like this, which are more bloated and three-dimensional than the mental image of samosas I had between my ears for most of my life. ⁣ ⁣ The ones here are salty and buttery and taste to me like deep-fried potato and pea pies.⁣ ⁣ I remember quite clearly when my dad introduced me to one of the other chaats available here, with its dressed potato and chickpea-filled shells, which he told me were called puchkas and I later learned was just one of many regional names for the same dish. ⁣ ⁣ When I had this menu item at Chini Chor on a sweltering day this week, where it’s called gol gappa, the cool, flavoured water it hinges on made me understand just how refreshing this dish can be. ⁣ ⁣ That same day the people behind me were all ordering ice cream, which I decided I should do on my next visit. ⁣ ⁣ So when I came back again on Wednesday I went for a delightfully elastic malai kulfi on a stick, which they offered to stagger the arrival of, so that it would come a short while after I’d finished my cup of tea.

properties.description:
East Street Market

I’ve been back to the seafood stall on East Street Market a few times lately, where a guy will measure out some cockles for you, pop them in a polystyrene cup, then kindly direct you towards the pepper, vinegar and cocktail sauce. ⁣ ⁣ I asked him how long he’s worked here and he said since the 1980s, but the stall itself has been around since before the war. ⁣ ⁣ “I’m old, but I’m not that old,” he told me.⁣ ⁣ You’ll find him here on Saturdays, when the market’s in full swing, at the Walworth Road end of East Street. ⁣ ⁣ I like to enter the market from Old Kent Road though, where it starts with just a smattering of stalls and you can feel it become progressively busier as you get deeper in, so things reach a crescendo when you arrive at the seafood stand. ⁣ ⁣ You can get stuff like whelks, shrimps, winkles, fish sticks and crab claws, but the cockles seem to be the most popular option, which a grandmotherly lady told me are from Southend before buying some herself. ⁣ ⁣ They taste to me like the seaside smells and I find them fascinating to look at, with their tender, pale grey bodies and orange tails curled up like tiny little organs.⁣ ⁣ As with the prawns and the rollmops, those pickled, rolled-up herring fillets, you’re left with what looks like cloudy seawater at the end. ⁣ ⁣ If you want to buy a bunch of these things and sit down to eat your shellfish bonanza nearby, I find that the benches on Liverpool Grove are a good option, in the paved area in front of St Peter’s Church.⁣ ⁣ The same goes for the seating by Southwark Heritage Centre, further up towards Elephant and Castle.⁣ ⁣ These places can feel at odds with such old-fashioned food, maybe because they're the result of relatively recent development work.⁣ ⁣ I remember thinking something similar when I passed Downey Brothers in Globe Town market in Bethnal Green, another seafood stall, which I thought contrasted in a pretty way with the stout post-war tower block behind it. ⁣ ⁣ I’d be interested to hear about other places in London like this, as Downey Brothers has since closed, but I gather there’s still seafood stands in Charlton and The Blue Market in Bermondsey.

New Cross

I went to @dr.noodle_2023 in New Cross three times within a week when it first opened, then immediately wrote about the place for @vittlesmagazine, back in May.⁣ ⁣ Usually when I go somewhere a lot in a short period and write about my experiences straight after, it takes me a while to feel like going back there, in the same way I need a bit of time before rewatching a film.⁣ ⁣ But I found myself returning to Dr. Noodle sooner than I thought, because the proprietors serve the kind of food I want to eat again and again.⁣ ⁣ Every time I go back, I notice something new has appeared, like a houseplant or a piece of artwork. ⁣ ⁣ Even with these decorative changes, the vibe has stayed similar, with the drinks fridge humming and cars swooshing by outside; occasionally there’s some tender, Studio Ghibli-esque piano music playing.⁣ ⁣ Food-wise, I’ve tried most of the noodle dishes now, some more than once, but I’m still not sure which one I like the most.⁣ ⁣ I remain particularly fascinated by the “peas and meat sauce” option though, which I learned from @fuchsiadunlop’s book The Food of Sichuan is better known as wanza mian, a type of Chongqing ‘small’ noodles.⁣ ⁣ This dish includes things like peanuts, ground pork and Sichuan pepper, but what really interests me are the sesame paste and yellow split peas in it, which make it taste a little earthy and are ingredients I hadn’t associated with Chinese food before. ⁣ ⁣ The fun thing is you mix everything around as you eat it, so the bowl of food you finish is quite different from the one you have at the beginning. ⁣ ⁣ I thought the place’s signage and menu might also contain details that don’t immediately show themselves, at least if you don’t speak Chinese, which I don’t. ⁣ ⁣ So I asked my friend Perry who does and he told me the three characters above Dr. Noodle’s sign have some cool wordplay going on, with different shades of meaning that could translate to something like "a treasured beautiful scoop" or “scooping for treasures”.⁣ ⁣ Perry also translated the longer tagline at the top of their menu, which he said means something similarly beautiful: “half a century of craftsmanship, just for a good bowl of noodles”.

properties.description:
Vasantha Vilas

Vasantha Vilas doesn’t have any of the distinctive furnishings or historical stuff that usually make me want to visit a restaurant, like interesting chairs, light fixtures or pictures on the walls.⁣ ⁣ But I’ve still found myself drawn back there repeatedly over the years, because I like the feel of the place and the food it serves.⁣ ⁣ I really enjoy eating breakfast there at the weekend or going there for an early dinner after work, before wandering around the local area and peering into the windows of other places I want to go to nearby. ⁣ ⁣ During late morning on a Sunday, Vasantha Vilas may be the busiest restaurant in East Ham, its simple, stripped-back dining room filled with chatter, babbling toddlers and people showing each other funny videos on their phones.⁣ ⁣ On a Wednesday evening it’s more placid, with a greater number of solo diners and couples than groups. ⁣ ⁣ The place makes me think that restaurants are really just public rooms with loads of tables, where someone will ask you what you want before other people cook it for you in the back, and the dish eventually materialises in front of you.⁣ ⁣ Vasantha Vilas isn’t as canteen-like as Wong Kei, but it feels functional and effective in a similar way that’s pleasing to see in action, like a windmill or a water wheel. ⁣ ⁣ The food tends to arrive quickly and when things are slightly slower because it’s busy, at least you can see why.⁣ ⁣ Whether the place is packed or not, I always go there intending to try a more ambitious dosa variant, like the rava dosa, but I usually end up sticking to the mini tiffin, where there’s a bit of everything as well as some dessert and you feel like you get more bang for your buck. ⁣ ⁣ That said, I have ordered the odd individual menu item, such as the plain uthappam, and still felt very satisfied.⁣ ⁣ I like how you tend to get at least four things to dip into, including a large thimble of sambar, that homely and quite sippable lentil, vegetable and moringa stew.⁣ ⁣ I find every component of the mini tiffin fun to eat, but I take particular pleasure in the ice cream scoop of pongal you get, and the cashew, curry leaves and peppercorns that nestle within its ricey mush.

properties.description:
Ayres the Bakers

One thing I find interesting about Ayres Bakery in Nunhead is its queue, which begins life as a loose, indistinct column of people, before building momentum and becoming more unified.⁣ ⁣ But just as quickly as it comes together, the queue disbands again, when its component parts branch out and people are called up to the place’s various counters to order. ⁣ ⁣ It’s at this point that you feel surrounded on all sides by baked goods, like you’re in the middle of a courtyard. ⁣ ⁣ This phenomenon is down to Ayres’ layout, in that all the display cases connect together to form one big U-shape, as they also do in other old bakeries like Yasar Halim on Green Lanes and Shalom Hot Bagels in Gants Hill. ⁣ ⁣ In the midst of all this, you may notice Ayres’ brown and harvest gold floor tiles, which have a nice gradient to them and remind me of the 1970s trains that run on the Bakerloo line.⁣ ⁣ The sign outside says the place opened 67 years ago and it looks to have been remodelled since, but I like to think this flooring could be among its older features.⁣ ⁣ 1955 also happens to be the year the butcher a few doors down opened, which is 58 years after the fishmonger, both of which this villagey street has somehow managed to sustain. ⁣ ⁣ I’ve thought about this stuff a few times lately, not long before I’ve ordered things like a pasty, a doughnut, a sausage roll and a ham and cheese sandwich.⁣ ⁣ I particularly like the pasty here, which is top-crimped rather than side-crimped, closer to an American football than a flat half-moon. ⁣ ⁣ This pasty also features enough butter to turn its paper wrapping translucent, which is actually worth making use of while you eat it, especially if you want your phone screen to recognise your thumbs afterwards. ⁣ ⁣ Doughnut-wise, I’ve only tried the jam ones so far and I like how gigantic they are; they’re filled with goo, but maintain their integrity and are also light and airy. ⁣ ⁣ I imagine lots of customers buy things like these, along with bread and other bits and bobs to enjoy at home, or in their car. ⁣ ⁣ But I usually find myself eating my purchases on a bench on Nunhead Green nearby, which I’ve noticed some other people doing too.

properties.description:
Scotti's Snack Bar

Thrilled to share my interview with the two kind-hearted brothers who run Scotti’s Snack Bar in Clerkenwell, Al and Max. ⁣⁣ ⁣⁣ You can read it for free in @vittlesmagazine, alongside some absolutely brilliant photos by @nicofroe.⁣⁣ ⁣⁣ I’ve added the article to the link in my bio and I’ll share it in my stories too. ⁣⁣ ⁣⁣ I love Scotti’s for loads of reasons, not just because it’s so old and atmospheric, but also because its owners serve exactly the kind of food I want to eat. ⁣⁣ ⁣⁣ It’s an extremely welcoming place too, which has both quietly evolved over the last six decades and somehow managed to stay the same, while a huge amount of social and economic change has taken place on its doorstep. ⁣⁣ ⁣⁣ A lot of this adaptability is down to Al and Max, who’ve lived above Scotti’s their whole life and learned from their parents who came here from Italy after the war. ⁣⁣ ⁣⁣ I’ve always wanted to tell a story like this and it’s a piece of writing I’m really proud of, which I hope you enjoy reading.

properties.description:
Wong Kei

I’ve amassed such a big bank of Wong Kei food pics over the years that I don’t really know what to do with them, so I’ve decided to just share a huge batch every now and then. For this one I’ve picked the dishes I find most photogenic, excluding the noodle soups, which are so pretty they deserve their own post. While I have lots to say about all of these delicious plates of food, what I love most about Wong Kei is its menu, how it feels to eat there and the place’s function as an inexpensive central London restaurant. So if you want to read about how these dishes taste, you should visit the Wong Kei Tumblr, the online archive which inspired me to order most of them. Through guiding my choices, this anonymous Tumblr also helped me discover how Wong Kei’s 300 item menu behaves and how seamless the process of ordering is here, particularly when you already know what you want. As with the Tumblr author, I’ve mostly been drawn to the solo diner-friendly sections, such as Rice, Special Meal and Barbecue Cold Meat on Hot Rice. By focusing on regions of the menu like this, you can see how key ingredients are mixed and matched throughout, a bit like a Rubik's Cube, in that the central components can stay constant regardless of the configuration you choose. One example here is the barbeque pork, which comes on top of rice or in soup, but shows up in lots of other places too, like the fried ho fun Malaysian. The same goes for the crispy noodles, which you could quite feasibly wish to have with the crispy belly pork, even though this combination isn’t on the menu. Other restaurants serve this dish and I’ve seen people ordering it here; the Tumblr person did too. Then there’s the gravy-like sauces, which appear again and again in different forms. You can see the siu mei guys ladling it out in dark, glossy puddles, while the lighter, gloopier version comes from the kitchen, where the ho fun and assorted meat dishes are made. Maybe it was these members of kitchen staff, who operate behind the scenes and I imagine whooshing great heaps of noodles in gigantic pans, that placed those tiny figurines into the nooks of the exposed stone wall downstairs.

properties.description:
New Atlas Cafe Restaurant

I’ve been having a whale of a time lately going to New Atlas Cafe in Harlesden, a spot I’ve been meaning to visit for ages. ⁣ ⁣ It reminds me a lot of the place that first sparked my interest in old caffs, Rock Steady Eddie’s in Camberwell, mainly because it sits on a main thoroughfare and is so well-used by people who live and work nearby. ⁣ ⁣ At peak times, there’s a steady stream of regulars passing through New Atlas Cafe’s doors, who greet the proprietors by name and bring their empty plates to the counter when they’re ready to pay; some of them even return their sauces to the drinks fridge. ⁣ ⁣ It’s an enormous caff really, with over 30 tables set across two clean, light-filled dining rooms, which sit parallel to each other like the barrels of a shotgun. ⁣ ⁣ Even though these huge, slate-grey rooms don't feel as old as they really are, you can still spot traces of an intriguing past, such as the ghost of a bar with a set of now defunct optic brackets, one of them still bearing a Bacardi label.⁣ ⁣ There’s plenty of period chairs dotted around too, mostly in the right-hand dining room, with these great curved backs and bobbled ears.⁣ ⁣ The place’s concise, inflation-busting menu seems similarly old-fashioned: just two varieties of fry-up and some classic main meal options, alongside more distinctive stuff like kleftiko and jelly with ice cream.⁣ ⁣ The first time I tried to order the kleftiko was on my second visit, when I learned it was only available on Fridays.⁣ ⁣ When I came back two days later, at 1pm, the kleftiko had already sold out, so I opted for the lamb chops, which I ate next to a pair of traffic wardens and two ladies with white hair and Irish accents. ⁣ ⁣ I’m a big fan of the fry-up here, which comes out in seconds, features real sausages and includes a generous amount of bacon; I like how you get serrated knives as standard too, since they make everything so much easier to cut.⁣ ⁣ Judging by his crisp shirt and shiny watch, my guess is all this efficiency is down to the kind, worldly-wise Greek Cypriot gentleman who runs the place. ⁣ ⁣ When I asked him how old his restaurant was, he told me he opened it in his late twenties, 51 years ago.

properties.description:
Diyarbakir Restaurant

Even when you only order one thing at Diyarbakir Restaurant, somehow you end up with three additional dishes and a superstrength cup of tea at the end, all at no extra charge.⁣ ⁣ Along with the salad, the charred onions, and the bread and dip that came before my mains, I’ve enjoyed everything I’ve actually asked for here.⁣ ⁣ On my first visit that dish was a small adana kebab, a coarse cylinder of lamb that tasted to me like a quarter pounder and bore the indentations of the hands that had pressed it into shape.⁣ ⁣ When I came back, I tried my first Iskender kebab, which I decided to order after consulting @jonathandnunn’s entry on the restaurant in his Eater London guide to Green Lanes.⁣ ⁣ I don’t think I’ve ever tasted anything like it, with its mix of dense yoghurt and fragments of tomatoey doner, more funky than roast grouse; texture-wise, the dish reminded me of kottu roti, since it featured chopped bread too.⁣ ⁣ During those visits the place’s cavernous dining room held only a smattering of people, just some couples and families chatting over platters of meat, along with the odd man working through a bowl of soup.⁣ ⁣ I think the restaurant’s usually busier; it’s more that I’ve mainly been just before 12, when it’s a bit early for lunch and most people have already had breakfast. ⁣ ⁣ But I like it when it’s quiet, since you get a feel for the dining room’s shape, with its brickwork arch in the middle like a canal tunnel.⁣ ⁣ It’s a straightforward place to eat, but still atmospheric, especially when the smells of fresh bread and charcoal-grilled meat drift into each other from either side of the room. ⁣ ⁣ Those smells were there when I had my first lamb soup and the place entirely to myself, until another guy arrived and ordered the same thing.⁣ ⁣ I like how the soup’s orange as hell – with all that butter and those soft cuboids of lamb – yet it doesn’t feel overly rich, which makes me think someone’s taken great care to balance everything out. ⁣ ⁣ I noticed a similar harmoniousness with the Mediterranean breakfast platter, which tasted way more complicated than it looked and cheered me up after I’d travelled to a caff nearby that turned out to be closed.

properties.description:
Mary's Cafè

I started going to Mary’s about five years ago now, back when I’d been living in and around Camberwell for a while and first got into visiting old caffs. ⁣ ⁣ In those days one of my favourite weekend activities was to take a left out of my front door and walk north, passing Rock Steady Eddies and Costa before crossing over to the McDonald’s side of the road and wandering up through Camberwell Green. ⁣ ⁣ If I wanted to, I could walk in the same direction for ages and eventually get to central London. ⁣ ⁣ But I usually got distracted by all the stuff on the way, like the ancient lime kiln in Burgess Park, the seafood stall on East Street and the Pullens Buildings, those ornate Victorian tenements off Walworth Road. ⁣ ⁣ When I go back today I’m still not sure where Camberwell ends and Walworth begins, but the hand-painted sign above the entrance to Mary’s remains one of my markers.⁣ ⁣ Inside, I love the place’s 16 slender tables, which are topped with mustard yellow Formica and surrounded by beautifully dinky mid-century chairs.⁣ ⁣ You may also notice the dining room’s grand spherical light fixtures, which hang from the high ceiling like blank, countryless globes and could be 58 years old if they were installed when Mary’s opened.⁣ ⁣ I’ve eaten some excellent breakfasts in this quiet, open room, beneath those antique lights.⁣ ⁣ While I prefer smaller fry-ups these days, I’ve thoroughly enjoyed the Irish breakfast at Mary’s, which includes white pudding and excludes baked beans here.⁣ ⁣ So maybe for me, Mary’s is just a pretty, historical room to eat big plates of cheap, satisfying food.⁣ ⁣ Though I think its main function is as a local hangout, for people who work or live around here, or want to spend time somewhere that isn’t their house.⁣ ⁣ On quieter afternoons you may find the place’s softly-spoken proprietor sitting and chatting with his customers, before getting up to take an order and shouting it politely into the hidden kitchen behind him.⁣ ⁣ He seems like a thoughtful, attentive guy, particularly when he checks if you have enough condiments with your meal, or when you ask about the distinctive artwork on his walls, which feature two portraits of him.

properties.description:
The Fryer's Delight

The first thing that got me interested in The Fryer’s Delight, that half century-old chip shop in Holborn, was its outstanding signage. ⁣ ⁣ I learned from @e.crow.illustration’s great book Shopfronts of London that the sign uses a typeface called Playbill, where the horizontal parts of each letter are extra thick. ⁣ ⁣ It’s the kind of thing you see on a wanted poster, which I’ve also seen called French Clarendon. ⁣ ⁣ When you go inside, there’s another cool bit of lettering too, written in forest green on the top right corner of the board behind the counter, which says “Take Away Menu” in a jagged handwriting style. ⁣ ⁣ You may recognise this typeface from Chicago house label Dance Mania, along with the logo for the film Drive.⁣ ⁣ All this signage plays a big part in the atmosphere here, as with the fans, the coral tables, the checkerboard floor, the double-length mirror, the cushioned booth seating and the brilliant mid-century modern coat stand. ⁣ ⁣ But I also think there’s a general energy to the restaurant which must be connected to the people who run it. ⁣ ⁣ The service is prompt and friendly, while the burly fry cook with the braces and beard tends to sing, hum or whistle as he cooks.⁣ ⁣ The place used to be Italian-run and its interior dates from those days, but it changed hands a while back and the guys who own it today are Portuguese – “from close to Porto,” one of them told me. ⁣ ⁣ When they're not cooking something or serving customers, I find it heartwarming how they just stand around and chat, like three good mates hanging out.⁣ ⁣ Someone always eventually pops in, at which point the polite bespectacled guy takes their order if they’re eating in, before quietly instructing his colleagues to fling a few items into the boiling fat.⁣ ⁣ I went a couple of times in the evening during winter, when it was dark and I felt this relaxed vibe especially strongly then.⁣ ⁣ I've been going back again lately and it feels much the same, with the benefit of some sun coming in through the windows. ⁣ ⁣ Regardless of the weather, the lights are always on though, which I was thrilled to find out recently are the exact same design as the ones at Scotti’s Snack Bar.

properties.description:
Merkato

Along with Addis, Agelgil, Sophe Cafe, Sweet Cafe, Marathon Restaurant and Ayni Internet Cafe, you may have noticed that Merkato is part of that cluster of restaurants that serve Ethiopian and Eritrean food on the lower section of Caledonian Road.⁣ ⁣ Out of all those places, I was drawn to Merkato mainly because its dining room looked so dramatic.⁣ ⁣ Fairy lights line the walls, oblong-framed musicians sit above the doorway and several ivy-clad umbrellas hang quite naturally from the ceiling, while the chairs have a different seat covering every time you visit. ⁣ ⁣ I noticed most of these features before I even went to Merkato, when I googled it; it was only by eating there that I got to know how the restaurant feels.⁣ ⁣ I like how there’s usually a small amount of fragrant smoke floating through the air, which becomes more pronounced if somebody gets the coffee, since the cups and the smooth, long-necked clay pot it's poured from are accompanied by a dedicated burner of incense.⁣ ⁣ The first time I really looked at one of those coffee pots, which I learned are called jebenas, I was sitting inside and soft Ethio-jazz was playing.⁣ ⁣ When I sat there again, the music was more gravelly-voiced blues rock, which made the place feel especially safe and sheltered while heavy rain fell on the portion of A5203 outside. ⁣ ⁣ It was sunny and I was sitting in the restaurant’s pleasant outdoor area when I tried my first tibs, which I liked because the lamb came in these small chunks and the sauce was so dark and deep.⁣ ⁣ As with some of the components of the vegan combo I tried, the tibs’s tomatoey elements reminded me a little of Bolognese, the kind that has been cooked for ages and may stain the inside of your lunchbox.⁣ ⁣ Even the menu is fun here, since a lot of the options are connected by rows and arrows. ⁣ ⁣ It can be confusing at first, but you soon realise how functional this layout is; it also feels good to order several dishes at once by sliding your finger down a column as you speak.⁣ ⁣ Still, I’ve been happy with just the one dish too, like my first kitfo, which came with a mix of cheese and spinach, piled into the same serving bowl like a spherical pie chart.

Along with Addis, Agelgil, Sophe Cafe, Sweet Cafe, Marathon Restaurant and Ayni Internet Cafe, you may have noticed that Merkato is part of that cluster of restaurants that serve Ethiopian and Eritrean food on the lower section of Caledonian Road.⁣
⁣
Out of all those places, I was drawn to Merkato mainly because its dining room looked so dramatic.⁣
⁣
Fairy lights line the walls, oblong-framed musicians sit above the doorway and several ivy-clad umbrellas hang quite naturally from the ceiling, while the chairs have a different seat covering every time you visit. ⁣
⁣
I noticed most of these features before I even went to Merkato, when I googled it; it was only by eating there that I got to know how the restaurant feels.⁣
⁣
I like how there’s usually a small amount of fragrant smoke floating through the air, which becomes more pronounced if somebody gets the coffee, since the cups and the smooth, long-necked clay pot it's poured from are accompanied by a dedicated burner of incense.⁣
⁣
The first time I really looked at one of those coffee pots, which I learned are called jebenas, I was sitting inside and soft Ethio-jazz was playing.⁣
⁣
When I sat there again, the music was more gravelly-voiced blues rock, which made the place feel especially safe and sheltered while heavy rain fell on the portion of A5203 outside. ⁣
⁣
It was sunny and I was sitting in the restaurant’s pleasant outdoor area when I tried my first tibs, which I liked because the lamb came in these small chunks and the sauce was so dark and deep.⁣
⁣
As with some of the components of the vegan combo I tried, the tibs’s tomatoey elements reminded me a little of Bolognese, the kind that has been cooked for ages and may stain the inside of your lunchbox.⁣
⁣
Even the menu is fun here, since a lot of the options are connected by rows and arrows. ⁣
⁣
It can be confusing at first, but you soon realise how functional this layout is; it also feels good to order several dishes at once by sliding your finger down a column as you speak.⁣
⁣
Still, I’ve been happy with just the one dish too, like my first kitfo, which came with a mix of cheese and spinach, piled into the same serving bowl like a spherical pie chart.
